The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Thursday, July 08, 2004 				 Police claim fake find in Mukti home 
 OUR BUREAU 																								July 7: As former Visva-Bharati vice-chancellor Dilip Sinha, arrested in connection with the recruitment of lecturer Mukti Deb on the basis of fake documents, prepared to face police, sleuths said they found more illegally attested marksheets in her house. 																								One blank  there were no scores in the boxes  Jadavpur University marksheet was attested in 1986 by the then headmaster of a district school. The marksheet was illegally attested as true copy of Jadavpur University, said public prosecutor Abul Naseem. 																								Two more blank marksheets were seized from her house which were illegally attested by a district commercial tax officer, said Naseem. 																								Sinha, who was admitted to hospital with chest pain, was brought to a Bolpur court that put him in police custody till July 9. Deb was remanded in judicial custody till July 21. 																								The prosecution opposed their bail petitions, saying the CID believes the duo had links as far back as 1980. 																								Deb today gave a statement to judicial magistrate Manoj Roy after police prayed that her confession be recorded. As it took only 15 to 20 minutes, some lawyers were of the opinion that Deb might have pleaded innocent. 																								The Congress and SUCI members walked out of the Assembly after the Speaker refused an adjournment motion on the row over Sinha and the PhD degree of former Rabindra Bharati vice-chancellor Pabitra Sarkar. Clarification																								A.K. Dutta, the technical director of Simplex Construction Piles (I) Ltd, today clarified Simplex is not associated with the construction of the six-lane flyover at Ch: 561 opposite Burdwan Purta Bhavan, a part of which collapsed yesterday. 
